748 || {{increase}} 14.6%  || 8,422,537 || {{increase}} 15.1%  || 7,556,696 || {{increase}} 18%\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! 2003<ref name=\"YYZStatistics2\"/>\n|24,739,312 ||&nbsp;\u2013\u2013\u2013\u2013  || 11,021,760 ||&nbsp;\u2013\u2013\u2013\u2013 || 7,316,287 ||&nbsp;\u2013\u2013\u2013\u2013 || 6,401,265 ||&nbsp;\u2013\u2013\u2013\u2013\n|}\n;Notes:\n*<small>{{note|c|c}}: For operational and statistical purposes, a distinction is made between \"transborder\" and \"international\" flights at Toronto Pearson and at any other airport in Canada with [[United States border preclearance]]. A \"transborder\" flight is a flight between Canada and a destination in the United States, while an \"international\" flight is a flight between Canada and a destination that is ''not'' within the United States or Canada, and a \"domestic\" flight is defined as a flight within the Canadian territories only.</small>\n\n==Incidents and accidents==\n<!--Incidents and accidents must occur at or near Pearson-->\n* On October 3, 1959, [[Vickers Viscount]] CF-TGY of [[Trans-Canada Air Lines]] was written off when it landed short of the runway.<ref name=ASN031159>{{cite web |url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19591003-0 |title=Accident description |publisher=[[Aviation Safety Network]] |accessdate=January 3, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121111114006/http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19591003-0 |archive-date=November 11, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> No fatalities among the 38 on board.\n* On February 10, 1960, a [[Lockheed L-1049 Super Constellation|Super Constellation]] of [[Trans-Canada Air Lines]] was seriously damaged when it overran the runway after landing in bad weather. None of the 59 passengers and crew were injured.<ref>{{cite news|periodical=Globe and Mail|location=Toronto|date=1960-02-11|page=1|title=      Skids Off Runway on Belly: 59 Safe in Crackup at Malton As Airliner Overshoots in Fog: TCA Plane Crashes Into Fence}}</ref>\n* On June 13, 1964, [[Vickers Viscount]] CF-THT of [[Air Canada]] was damaged beyond economical repair when it crash-landed after the failure of two engines on approach.<ref name=ASN130664>{{cite web |url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19640613-1 |title=Accident description |publisher=Aviation Safety Network |accessdate=October 6, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025091126/http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19640613-1 |archive-date=October 25, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* The airport's deadliest accident occurred on July 5, 1970, when [[Air Canada Flight 621]], a [[Douglas DC-8|DC-8]] jet, flew on a Montreal\u2013Toronto\u2013Los Angeles route. The pilots inadvertently deployed [[spoiler (aeronautics)|spoiler]]s before the plane attempted [[landing]], forcing the pilots to abort landing and [[takeoff]]. Damage to the aircraft that was caused during the failed landing attempt caused the plane to break up in the air during the [[go-around]], killing all 100 passengers and nine [[Aircrew|crew members]] on board when it crashed into a field southeast of [[Brampton]]. Controversy remains over the cleanup effort following the crash, as both plane wreckage debris and human remains from the crash are still found on the site.<ref name=\"wilkes\">{{cite news| last=Wilkes| first=Jim| date=July 6, 2004| url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/thestar/access/668477591.html?dids=668477591:668477591&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Jul+6%2C+2004&author=Jim+Wilkes&pub=Toronto+Star&edition=&startpage=A.01| title=Ghosts of Flight 621 haunt Brampton field| page=A1| work=Toronto Star| accessdate=January 3, 2013| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103204858/http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/thestar/access/668477591.html?dids=668477591:668477591&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Jul+6,+2004&author=Jim+Wilkes&pub=Toronto+Star&edition=&startpage=A.01| archive-date=November 3, 2012| url-status=live}}</ref>\n* On August 30, 1970, [[Douglas C-47 Skytrain|Douglas C-47]] CF-JRY of D G Harris Productions was damaged beyond economic repair in a storm.<ref name=ASN300870>{{cite web |url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19700830-0 |title=CF-JRY Hull-loss description |publisher=Aviation Safety Network |accessdate=October 20, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103065315/http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19700830-0 |archive-date=November 3, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* On June 21, 1973, [[Air Canada]] Flight 890, a DC-8-53 (CF-TIJ), was destroyed by fire during refueling at the gate.<ref name=\"eastwood\">Eastwood and Roach 1992, pp.339\u2013363. This source incorrectly spells the Wasatch range as \"Wasateh\".</ref>\n* On June 26, 1978, [[Air Canada Flight 189]] to [[Winnipeg]] overran the runway during an [[Rejected takeoff|aborted takeoff]], and crashed into the [[Etobicoke Creek]] [[ravine]]. Two of the 107 passengers on board the [[McDonnell Douglas DC-9|DC-9]] were killed.\n*On June 22, 1983, [[Douglas C-47 Skytrain|Douglas C-47A]] C-GUBT of [[Skycraft Air Transport]] crashed on takeoff roll at Toronto International Airport while on an international cargo flight from [[Cleveland Hopkins International Airport]] in northeastern [[Ohio]]. Both of the crew members were killed.<ref name=ASN220683>{{cite web |url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19830622-0 |title=C-GUBT Accident report |publisher=Aviation Safety Network |accessdate=July 27, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102154333/http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19830622-0 |archive-date=November 2, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* On August 2, 2005, [[Air France Flight 358]], an [[Airbus A340|Airbus A340-300]] (registration F-GLZQ) inbound from Paris, landed on runway 24L during a severe thunderstorm, failed to stop, and ran off of the runway into the Etobicoke Creek ravine. The rear third of the plane burst into flames, eventually engulfing the whole plane except the [[cockpit]] and [[wing]]s. There were 12 serious injuries, but no fatalities. The investigation predominantly blamed pilot error when faced with the severe weather conditions.<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.bst-tsb.gc.ca/eng/rapports-reports/aviation/2005/a05h0002/a05h0002.asp|title= Aviation Investigation Report - Runway Overrun and Fire - Air France Airbus 340-313 F-GLZQ - Toronto/Lester B. Pearson International Airport, Ontario - 02 August 2005 - Report Number A05H0002|publisher= [[Transportation Safety Board of Canada]]|isbn= 978-0-662-47298-8|id= Public Works and Government Services Canada Cat. No. TU3-5/05-3E|year= 2007|access-date= December 13, 2007|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160319094421/http://www.bst-tsb.gc.ca/eng/rapports-reports/aviation/2005/a05h0002/a05h0002.asp|archive-date= March 19, 2016|url-status= live}} <nowiki>[</nowiki>Aussi disponible en fran\u00e7ais&nbsp;: \"[http://www.bst-tsb.gc.ca/fra/rapports-reports/aviation/2005/a05h0002/a05h0002.asp Rapport d'enqu\u00eate a\u00e9ronautique A05H0002] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170331022155/http://bst-tsb.gc.ca/fra/rapports-reports/aviation/2005/a05h0002/a05h0002.asp |date=March 31, 2017 }}\"</ref>\n* On July 25, 2014, [[Sunwing Airlines]] Flight 772, which had taken off from Toronto bound for [[Scarlett Mart\u00ednez International Airport]], was forced to return to Toronto after a passenger made a [[bomb threat]]; the plane landed safely and the passenger was arrested.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://toronto.citynews.ca/2014/07/25/passengers-alleged-bomb-threat-forces-sunwing-flight-back-to-pearson/|title=Passenger's alleged bomb threat forces Sunwing flight back to Pearson|publisher=toronto.citynews.ca|date=July 25, 2014}}</ref>\n* On May 10, 2019, Air Canada Flight 8615, a [[Bombardier Dash 8|Bombardier DHC-8-300]], was struck by a fuel truck while taxiing on the tarmac. Five persons were injured and the plane was deemed a write-off.<ref>{{cite web |title='Incredibly scary': Air Canada plane, fuel tanker collide at Toronto's Pearson airport |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/air-canada-jazz-fuel-tanker-truck-pearson-collision-1.5130624 |website=cbc.ca |publisher=CBC News |accessdate=10 May 2019 |date=10 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510135045/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/air-canada-jazz-fuel-tanker-truck-pearson-collision-1.5130624 |archive-date=May 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n<!--Incidents and accidents must occur at or near Pearson-->\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Canada|Ontario|Aviation}}\n* [[CFBN]]\n* [[History of Toronto Pearson International Airport]]\n* [[List of airports in the Greater Toronto Area]]\n* [[YYZ (Rush song)|YYZ]], a song named after the airport's IATA code by Canadian band Rush\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<!-- <ref name=GlobeAndMail2017-02-07>\n{{cite news                     \n| url         = https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/toronto/pearson-unveils-early-concept-for-transit-hub/article33931364/\n| title       = Toronto's Pearson airport unveils early concept for transit hub\n| work   = [[The Globe and Mail]]\n| author      = Oliver Moore\n| date        = February 7, 2017\n| accessdate  = February 8, 2017\n| quote       = But the biggest change would be making Pearson more accessible to transit. Advocates call for it to become a sort of Union Station for the western side of city \u2013 albeit one that would serve far fewer people than the station downtown.\n}}\n</ref> -->\n\n<!-- <ref name=Cbc2017-02-07>\n{{cite news \n| url         = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/pearson-airport-development-1.3968790\n| title       = Toronto's Pearson International Airport unveils design for new transit hub: Mega-project would provide more connections with rail and bus lines\n| publisher   = [[CBC News]]\n| author      = John Rieti\n| date        = February 7, 2017\n| accessdate  = February 8, 2017\n| quote       = The Greater Toronto Airports Authority (GTAA) released new images of the multi-modal transit centre it wants to build across from Pearson's two main terminals by 2027.\n}}\n</ref> -->\n\n<!-- <ref name=Insauga2017-02-07>\n{{cite news \n| title       = Pearson Airport Set to Welcome Massive New Project\n| publisher   = [[Insauga]]\n| author      = Ashley Newport\n| date        = February 7, 2017\n| accessdate  = February 8, 2017\n| quote       = The GTAA said it's moving forward with plans for a regional transit centre (think of Union Station) to better connect the Pearson Airport area to \"key employment and residential areas throughout the Greater Golden Horseshoe.\" The proposed regional transit centre will also be home to airport passenger processing and security screening.\n}}\n</ref> -->\n\n<ref name=InfieldLounge>{{cite news\n |url         = http://www.expressvoyage.ca/reportages.php?sequence_no=3300\n |title       = Air Canada opens new Maple Leaf Lounge at the Infield Terminal at Toronto Pearson Airport\n |publisher   = Express Voyage\n |date        = February 10, 2005\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20140917132343/http://www.expressvoyage.ca/reportages.php?sequence_no=3300\n |archivedate = September 17, 2014\n |url-status  = dead\n |quote       = Air Canada will officially open its newest Maple Leaf Lounge at the Infield Terminal at Toronto Pearson Airport on February 10, 2005.\n |access-date = September 17, 2014\n}}</ref>\n<ref name=BhArchInfield>\n{{cite news \n| url         = http://www.bharchitects.com/en/projects/168\n| title       = Toronto Pearson International Airport - Infield Development Project\n| publisher   = Bharchitects\n| date        = 2013\n| archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20131114230755/http://www.bharchitects.com/en/projects/168\n| archivedate=November 14, 2013\n| url-status     = live \n| quote       = Located on a {{convert|470|acre|ha|disp=sqbr|adj=on}} site between four major runways, this $250 million development is Canada's largest design-build project and {{sic|comprised |hide=y|of}} six structures totaling 1,356,360 square feet: the Air Canada Maintenance Building, three cargo buildings including the Air Canada Cargo Terminal, a 3-bay Hangar Facility, and the 11-gate Infield Holdroom Terminal.\n}}\n</ref>\n<!--<ref name=Inf1>\n{{cite news \n| url         = http://airwaysnews.com/blog/2014/01/29/toronto-pearson-airport-history/\n| title       = Toronto Pearson International Airport, Then and Now: Part Two\n| publisher   = [[Airway News]]\n| author      = Howard Slutsken\n| date        = June 2, 2014\n| archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20140917132335/http://airwaysnews.com/blog/2014/01/29/toronto-pearson-airport-history/\n| archivedate = September 17, 2014\n| url-status     = live \n| quote       = Consequently a new infield cargo, hangar, operations complex and eleven-gate Infield Terminal were built to allow the phased demolition and construction of the project to occur. The infield complex was linked to the terminal buildings by a new tunnel under Runway 15L/33R.\n}}\n</ref>-->\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{wikivoyage|Toronto Pearson International Airport}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.torontopearson.com/}}\n*[http://www.mississauga.ca/file/COM/9634_MaltonBook.pdf Malton: Farms to Flying Book by Kathleen A. Hicks - PDF]\n{{Can-arpt-wx|CYYZ|Toronto Pearson International Airport}}\n*[https://www.airportsdata.net/airport-YYZ/ Toronto Pearson airport travel data] at Airportsdata.net\n\n{{Airports in Ontario}}\n{{List of airports in Canada}}\n{{Toronto}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Toronto Pearson International Airport|*]]\n[[Category:Certified airports in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Mississauga]]\n[[Category:Transport in Mississauga]]\n[[Category:Transport in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Canadian airports with United States border preclearance]]\n[[Category:1938 establishments in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Airports established in 1938]]\n[[Category:National Airports System]]\n[[Category:Royal Canadian Air Force stations]]\n[[Category:Military airbases in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Airports of the British Commonwealth Air Training Plan]]\n[[Category:Military history of Ontario]]\n", "name_user": "Johnj1995", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Toronto_Pearson_International_Airport"}
{"title_page": "Gary Merrill", "text_new": "{{short description|Film and television character actor from the United States}}\n{{more citations needed|date=March 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name            = Gary Merrill\n| image           = Gary merrill.png\n| caption         = Merrill in the trailer for ''A Blueprint for Murder'' (1953)\n| birthname       = Gary Fred Merrill\n| birth_date      = {{birth date|1915|08|02}}\n| birth_place     = [[Hartford, Connecticut]], U.S.\n| death_date      = {{death date and age|1990|03|05|1915|08|02}}\n| death_place     = [[Falmouth, Maine]], U.S.\n| yearsactive     = 1943\u20131980\n| occupation      = Actor, director \n| spouse          = {{marriage|Barbara Leeds <br>|1941|1950|end=div}}<br>{{marriage|[[Bette Davis]] <br>|1950|1960|end=div}}\n| children        = 3\n}}\n\n'''Gary Fred Merrill''' (August 2, 1915 &ndash; March 5, 1990) was an American film and television actor whose credits included more than 50 feature films, a half-dozen mostly short-lived TV series, and dozens of television guest appearances. Merrill starred in ''[[All About Eve]]'' and married his co-star [[Bette Davis]].\n\n==Life and career==\nBorn in Hartford, Connecticut, he attended private Bowdoin College in Brunswick, Maine, and Trinity College<ref name=nyt/> and began acting in 1944, while still in the [[United States Army Air Forces]], in the play ''[[Winged Victory (play)|Winged Victory]]''. Before entering films, Merrill's deep cultured voice won him a recurring role as [[Batman]] in the ''Superman'' radio series. His film career began promisingly, with roles in films like ''[[Twelve O'Clock High]]'' (1949) and ''[[All About Eve]]'' (1950), but he rarely moved beyond supporting roles in his many Westerns, war movies, and medical dramas. His television career was extensive. He appeared from 1954-1956 as Jason Tyler on the crime drama ''[[Justice (1954 TV series)|Justice]]''.<ref>Alex McNeil, ''Total Television'', p. 444</ref>\n\nIn 1958, Merrill guest starred with [[June Lockhart]] in the roles of Joshua and Emily Newton in the episode \"Medicine Man\" of the series ''[[Cimarron City (TV series)|Cimarron City]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ctva.biz/US/Western/CimarronCity.htm|title=''Cimarron City''|publisher=ctva.biz|accessdate=September 8, 2012}}</ref>\n\nMerrill had recurring roles in ''[[Then Came Bronson]]'' with [[Michael Parks]] and ''[[Young Dr. Kildare (TV series)|Young Doctor Kildare]]'', both of which lasted less than a season.\n\nIn addition to Merrill's starring roles in several episodes of ''Alfred Hitchcock Presents'', in November 1963 he starred with Phyllis Thaxter and Fess Parker (''Daniel Boone'') in a memorable episode of ''The Alfred Hitchcock Hour'' (\"Nothing Ever Happens in Linvale\").\n\nIn 1964, he starred as [[city editor]] Lou Sheldon in the short-lived drama ''[[The Reporter (TV series)|The Reporter]]''.\n\nIn 1967, he starred in the [[Elvis Presley]] film ''[[Clambake (film)|Clambake]]'', with co-star [[James Gregory (actor)|James Gregory]].\n\nMerrill's first marriage, to Barbara Leeds in 1941, ended in divorce in Mexico on July 28, 1950. That same day, he married [[Bette Davis]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Bette Davis, Gary Merrill Wed In Mexico|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/56349867/?terms=%22Gary%2BMerrill%22|agency=Dunkirk Evening Observer|date=July 29, 1950|page=5|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = May 23, 2015}} {{Open access}}</ref> his co-star from ''All About Eve'', and adopted her daughter [[B.D. Hyman|Barbara]] from a previous marriage. He and Davis adopted two more children, Margo and Michael,<ref name=nyt/> but they had a bitter divorce in 1960.\n\nOften politically active, he campaigned in 1958 to elect the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] [[Edmund Muskie]] as governor of Maine. Merrill also took part in the [[Selma to Montgomery marches]] in 1965 to promote Black voter registration. In response to U.S. President [[Lyndon B. Johnson]]'s Vietnam War policy, he unsuccessfully sought nomination to the Maine legislature as an anti-war, pro-environmentalist primary candidate.<ref name=nyt>{{cite news|last1=Yarrow|first1=Andrew L.|title=Gary Merrill, Actor, Dies at 74; Worked in More Than 40 Films|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/03/07/obituaries/gary-merrill-actor-dies-at-74-worked-in-more-than-40-films.html|accessdate=2 January 2017|agency=New York Times|date=March 7, 1990}}</ref>\n\nAside from an occasional role as narrator, Merrill essentially retired from the entertainment business after 1980. Shortly before his death, he authored the autobiography ''Bette, Rita and the Rest of My Life'' (1989).\n\n==Death==\nMerrill survived his second former wife, [[Bette Davis]], by only five months, dying of lung cancer in Falmouth, Maine on March 5, 1990. He is buried there in the Pine Grove Cemetery. He was survived by a son,  Michael; a daughter, Margot; a brother, Jerry; and two grandchildren.<ref name=nyt/>\n\n==Television==\nMerrill's television work spanned from 1953\u20131980. Most of his appearances were in guest-star roles in episodic and [[anthology series]]. Among the programs in which Merrill appeared are: ''[[The 20th Century-Fox Hour]]'', ''[[Wagon Train]]'', ''[[Studio 57]]'', ''[[Studio One (TV series)|Studio One]]'', ''[[Playhouse 90]]'', ''[[Alcoa Theatre]]'', ''[[Rawhide (TV series)|Rawhide]]'', ''[[Laramie (TV series)|Laramie]]'', ''[[Cimarron City (TV series)|Cimarron City]]'', [[Sam Benedict]]'', ''[[Alfred Hitchcock Presents]]'' (numerous episodes, including \"Man With A Problem\" 1957 and \"O Youth and Beauty\" 1960), ''[[Zane Grey Theater]]'', ''[[The Twilight Zone (1959 TV series)|The Twilight Zone]]'' (episode \"[[Still Valley]]\" as Confederate soldier Joseph Paradine), ''[[General Electric Theater]]'', ''[[Ben Casey]]'', ''[[Combat!]]'', ''[[The Human Factor (1963 The Outer Limits)|The Outer Limits]]'', ''[[Bob Hope Presents the Chrysler Theatre]]'', ''[[Voyage to the Bottom of the Sea (TV series)|Voyage to the Bottom of the Sea]]'', ''[[The Time Tunnel]]'', ''[[Marcus Welby, M.D.]]'', ''[[Medical Center (TV series)|Medical Center]]'', ''[[Kung Fu (TV series)|Kung Fu]]'', ''[[Cannon (TV series)|Cannon]]'' and ''[[Movin' On (TV series)|Movin' On]]''.\n\nMerrill also served as narrator of the 1972\u201373 TV series ''The American Adventure''.\n\n==Filmography==\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*''[[This Is the Army]]'' (1943) - Backstage MP on Right (uncredited)\n*''[[Winged Victory (film)|Winged Victory]]'' (1944) - Capt. McIntyre \n*''[[Slattery's Hurricane]]'' (1949) - Cmdr. E.T. Kramer\n*''[[Twelve O'Clock High]]'' (1949) - Col. Keith Davenport\n*''[[Mother Didn't Tell Me]]'' (1950) - Doctor Peter Roberts\n*''[[Where the Sidewalk Ends (film)|Where the Sidewalk Ends]]'' (1950) - Tommy Scalise\n*''[[All About Eve]]'' (1950) - Bill Sampson (A typographical error in the film's credits lists the character's name as \"Simpson.)\n*''[[Rawhide (1951 film)|Rawhide]]'' (1951) - Narrator (voice, uncredited)\n*''[[The Frogmen]]'' (1951) - Lt. Cmdr. Pete Vincent\n*''[[Another Man's Poison]]'' (1951) - George Bates\n*''[[Decision Before Dawn]]'' (1951) - Col. Devlin\n*''[[Phone Call from a Stranger]]'' (1952) - David Trask\n*''[[The Girl in White]]'' (1952) - Dr. Seth Pawling\n*''[[Night Without Sleep]]'' (1952) - Richard Morton\n*''[[A Blueprint for Murder]]'' (1953) - Fred Sargent\n*''[[Witness to Murder]]'' (1954) - Lawrence Mathews\n*''[[The Black Dakotas]]'' (1954) - Brock Marsh posing as Zachary Paige\n*''[[The Human Jungle (film)|The Human Jungle]]'' (1954) - Police Capt. John Danforth\n*''[[Navy Wife]]'' (1956) - Jack Blain\n*''[[Bermuda Affair]]'' (1956) - Bob Scoffield\n*''[[The Missouri Traveler]]'' (1958) - Doyle Magee\n*''[[Crash Landing (1958 film)|Crash Landing]]'' (1958) - Capt. Steve Williams\n*''[[The Wonderful Country]]'' (1959) - Maj. Stark Colton\n*''[[The Savage Eye]]'' (1960) - The poet\n*''[[The Great Impostor]]'' (1961) - Pa Demara\n*''[[The Pleasure of His Company]]'' (1961) - James Dougherty\n*''[[Mysterious Island (1961 film)|Mysterious Island]]'' (1961) - Gideon Spilitt\n*''[[A Girl Named Tamiko]]'' (1962) - Max Wilson\n*''Hong Kong un Addio'' (''Farewell to Hong Kong'', 1963)\n*''The Searching Eye'' (1964) - Narrator\n*''[[Catacombs (1965 film)|Catacombs]]'' (1965) - Raymond Garth\n*''[[Ride Beyond Vengeance]]'' (1966) - Dub Stokes\n*''[[Cast a Giant Shadow]]'' (1966) - Pentagon Chief of Staff (scenes deleted)\n*''[[Destination Inner Space]]'' (1966) - Dr. LaSatier\n*''[[Around the World Under the Sea]]'' (1966) - Dr. August 'Gus' Boren\n*''[[The Last Challenge (1967)|The Last Challenge]]'' (1967) - Squint Calloway\n*''[[Clambake (film)|Clambake]]'' (1967) - Sam\n*''[[The Incident (1967 film)|The Incident]]'' (1967) - Douglas McCann\n*''[[The Power (1968 film)|The Power]]'' (1968) - Mark Corlane\n*''[[Pi\u00f9 tardi, Claire, pi\u00f9 tardi]]'' (1968) - George Dennison\n*''[[Amarsi male]]'' (1969)\n*''The Secret of the Sacred Forest'' (1970) - Mike Parks\n*''[[Earth II]]'' (1971) - Walter Dietrich\n*''[[Huckleberry Finn (1974 film)|Huckleberry Finn]]'' (1974) - Pap\n*''[[Thieves]]'' (1977) - Street Man\n*''[[The Seekers (1979 film)|The Seekers]]'' (1979) - Capt. Hull\n*''September Song'' (1984)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Radio appearances==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Program !! Episode/source\n|-\n| 1952|| ''[[Lux Radio Theatre]]'' || ''[[Follow the Sun (film)|Follow the Sun]]''<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kirby|first1=Walter|title=Better Radio Programs for the Week|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/2477300/the_decatur_daily_review/|agency=The Decatur Daily Review|date=March 9, 1952|page=42|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = May 25, 2015}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1952|| ''Hollywood Star Playhouse'' || \"The Patient Stranger\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kirby|first1=Walter|title=Better Radio Programs for the Week|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/2426009/the_decatur_daily_review/|agency=The Decatur Daily Review|date=April 6, 1952|page=52|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = May 16, 2015}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1953|| ''[[Lux Radio Theatre]]'' || ''[[Phone Call from a Stranger]]''<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kirby|first1=Walter|title=Better Radio Programs for the Week|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/2648002/the_decatur_daily_review/|agency=The Decatur Daily Review|date=January 4, 1953|page=38|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = June 19, 2015}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n*{{IMDb name|0581282}}\n*{{IBDB name}}\n*{{Find a Grave|4144}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Merrill, Gary}}\n[[Category:1915 births]]\n[[Category:1990 deaths]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Maine]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male radio actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:Bowdoin College alumni]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in Maine]]\n[[Category:Deaths from lung cancer]]\n[[Category:Maine Democrats]]\n[[Category:People from Falmouth, Maine]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Hartford, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:20th Century Fox contract players]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Film and television character actor from the United States}}\n{{refimprove|date=March 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name            = Gary Merrill\n| image           = Gary merrill.png\n| caption         = Merrill in the trailer for ''A Blueprint for Murder'' (1953)\n| birthname       = Gary Fred Merrill\n| birth_date      = {{birth date|1915|08|02}}\n| birth_place     = [[Hartford, Connecticut]], U.S.\n| death_date      = {{death date and age|1990|03|05|1915|08|02}}\n| death_place     = [[Falmouth, Maine]], U.S.\n| yearsactive     = 1943\u20131980\n| occupation      = Actor, director \n| spouse          = {{marriage|Barbara Leeds <br>|1941|1950|end=div}}<br>{{marriage|[[Bette Davis]] <br>|1950|1960|end=div}}\n| children        = 3\n}}\n\n'''Gary Fred Merrill''' (August 2, 1915 &ndash; March 5, 1990) was an American film and television actor whose credits included more than 50 feature films, a half-dozen mostly short-lived TV series, and dozens of television guest appearances. Merrill starred in ''[[All About Eve]]'' and married his co-star [[Bette Davis]].\n\n==Life and career==\nBorn in Hartford, Connecticut, he attended private Bowdoin College in Brunswick, Maine, and Trinity College<ref name=nyt/> and began acting in 1944, while still in the [[United States Army Air Forces]], in the play ''[[Winged Victory (play)|Winged Victory]]''. Before entering films, Merrill's deep cultured voice won him a recurring role as [[Batman]] in the ''Superman'' radio series. His film career began promisingly, with roles in films like ''[[Twelve O'Clock High]]'' (1949) and ''[[All About Eve]]'' (1950), but he rarely moved beyond supporting roles in his many Westerns, war movies, and medical dramas. His television career was extensive. He appeared from 1954-1956 as Jason Tyler on the crime drama ''[[Justice (1954 TV series)|Justice]]''.<ref>Alex McNeil, ''Total Television'', p. 444</ref>\n\nIn 1958, Merrill guest starred with [[June Lockhart]] in the roles of Joshua and Emily Newton in the episode \"Medicine Man\" of the series ''[[Cimarron City (TV series)|Cimarron City]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ctva.biz/US/Western/CimarronCity.htm|title=''Cimarron City''|publisher=ctva.biz|accessdate=September 8, 2012}}</ref>\n\nMerrill had recurring roles in ''[[Then Came Bronson]]'' with [[Michael Parks]] and ''[[Young Dr. Kildare (TV series)|Young Doctor Kildare]]'', both of which lasted less than a season.\n\nIn addition to Merrill's starring roles in several episodes of ''Alfred Hitchcock Presents'', in November 1963 he starred with Phyllis Thaxter and Fess Parker (''Daniel Boone'') in a memorable episode of ''The Alfred Hitchcock Hour'' (\"Nothing Ever Happens in Linvale\").\n\nIn 1964, he starred as [[city editor]] Lou Sheldon in the short-lived drama ''[[The Reporter (TV series)|The Reporter]]''.\n\nIn 1967, he starred in the [[Elvis Presley]] film ''[[Clambake (film)|Clambake]]'', with co-star [[James Gregory (actor)|James Gregory]].\n\nMerrill's first marriage, to Barbara Leeds in 1941, ended in divorce in Mexico on July 28, 1950. That same day, he married [[Bette Davis]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Bette Davis, Gary Merrill Wed In Mexico|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/56349867/?terms=%22Gary%2BMerrill%22|agency=Dunkirk Evening Observer|date=July 29, 1950|page=5|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = May 23, 2015}} {{Open access}}</ref> his co-star from ''All About Eve'', and adopted her daughter [[B.D. Hyman|Barbara]] from a previous marriage. He and Davis adopted two more children, Margo and Michael,<ref name=nyt/> but they had a bitter divorce in 1960.\n\nOften politically active, he campaigned in 1958 to elect the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] [[Edmund Muskie]] as governor of Maine. Merrill also took part in the [[Selma to Montgomery marches]] in 1965 to promote Black voter registration. In response to U.S. President [[Lyndon B. Johnson]]'s Vietnam War policy, he unsuccessfully sought nomination to the Maine legislature as an anti-war, pro-environmentalist primary candidate. <ref name=nyt>{{cite news|last1=Yarrow|first1=Andrew L.|title=Gary Merrill, Actor, Dies at 74; Worked in More Than 40 Films|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/03/07/obituaries/gary-merrill-actor-dies-at-74-worked-in-more-than-40-films.html|accessdate=2 January 2017|agency=New York Times|date=March 7, 1990}}</ref>\n\nAside from an occasional role as narrator, Merrill essentially retired from the entertainment business after 1980. Shortly before his death, he authored the autobiography ''Bette, Rita and the Rest of My Life'' (1989).\n\n==Death==\nMerrill survived his second former wife, [[Bette Davis]], by only five months, dying of lung cancer in Falmouth, Maine on March 5, 1990. He is buried there in the Pine Grove Cemetery. He was survived by a son,  Michael; a daughter, Margot; a brother, Jerry; and two grandchildren.<ref name=nyt/>\n\n==Television==\nMerrill's television work spanned from 1953-1980. Most of his appearances were in guest-star roles in episodic and [[anthology series]]. Among the programs in which Merrill appeared are: ''[[The 20th Century-Fox Hour]]'', ''[[Wagon Train]]'', ''[[Studio 57]]'', ''[[Studio One (TV series)|Studio One]]'', ''[[Playhouse 90]]'', ''[[Alcoa Theatre]]'', ''[[Rawhide (TV series)|Rawhide]]'', ''[[Laramie (TV series)|Laramie]]'', ''[[Cimarron City (TV series)|Cimarron City]]'', [[Sam Benedict]]'', ''[[Alfred Hitchcock Presents]]'' (numerous episodes, including \"Man With A Problem\" 1957 and \"O Youth and Beauty\" 1960), ''[[Zane Grey Theater]]'', ''[[The Twilight Zone (1959 TV series)|The Twilight Zone]]'' (episode \"[[Still Valley]]\" as Confederate soldier Joseph Paradine), ''[[General Electric Theater]]'', ''[[Ben Casey]]'', ''[[Combat!]]'', ''[[The Human Factor (1963 The Outer Limits)|The Outer Limits]]'', ''[[Bob Hope Presents the Chrysler Theatre]]'', ''[[Voyage to the Bottom of the Sea (TV series)|Voyage to the Bottom of the Sea]]'', ''[[The Time Tunnel]]'', ''[[Marcus Welby, M.D.]]'', ''[[Medical Center (TV series)|Medical Center]]'', ''[[Kung Fu (TV series)|Kung Fu]]'', ''[[Cannon (TV series)|Cannon]]'' and ''[[Movin' On (TV series)|Movin' On]]''.\n\nMerrill also served as narrator of the 1972\u201373 TV series ''The American Adventure''.\n\n==Filmography==\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*''[[This Is the Army]]'' (1943) - Backstage MP on Right (uncredited)\n*''[[Winged Victory (film)|Winged Victory]]'' (1944) - Capt. McIntyre \n*''[[Slattery's Hurricane]]'' (1949) - Cmdr. E.T. Kramer\n*''[[Twelve O'Clock High]]'' (1949) - Col. Keith Davenport\n*''[[Mother Didn't Tell Me]]'' (1950) - Doctor Peter Roberts\n*''[[Where the Sidewalk Ends (film)|Where the Sidewalk Ends]]'' (1950) - Tommy Scalise\n*''[[All About Eve]]'' (1950) - Bill Sampson (A typographical error in the film's credits lists the character's name as \"Simpson.)\n*''[[Rawhide (1951 film)|Rawhide]]'' (1951) - Narrator (voice, uncredited)\n*''[[The Frogmen]]'' (1951) - Lt. Cmdr. Pete Vincent\n*''[[Another Man's Poison]]'' (1951) - George Bates\n*''[[Decision Before Dawn]]'' (1951) - Col. Devlin\n*''[[Phone Call from a Stranger]]'' (1952) - David Trask\n*''[[The Girl in White]]'' (1952) - Dr. Seth Pawling\n*''[[Night Without Sleep]]'' (1952) - Richard Morton\n*''[[A Blueprint for Murder]]'' (1953) - Fred Sargent\n*''[[Witness to Murder]]'' (1954) - Lawrence Mathews\n*''[[The Black Dakotas]]'' (1954) - Brock Marsh posing as Zachary Paige\n*''[[The Human Jungle (film)|The Human Jungle]]'' (1954) - Police Capt. John Danforth\n*''[[Navy Wife]]'' (1956) - Jack Blain\n*''[[Bermuda Affair]]'' (1956) - Bob Scoffield\n*''[[The Missouri Traveler]]'' (1958) - Doyle Magee\n*''[[Crash Landing (1958 film)|Crash Landing]]'' (1958) - Capt. Steve Williams\n*''[[The Wonderful Country]]'' (1959) - Maj. Stark Colton\n*''[[The Savage Eye]]'' (1960) - The poet\n*''[[The Great Impostor]]'' (1961) - Pa Demara\n*''[[The Pleasure of His Company]]'' (1961) - James Dougherty\n*''[[Mysterious Island (1961 film)|Mysterious Island]]'' (1961) - Gideon Spilitt\n*''[[A Girl Named Tamiko]]'' (1962) - Max Wilson\n*''Hong Kong un Addio'' (''Farewell to Hong Kong'', 1963)\n*''The Searching Eye'' (1964) - Narrator\n*''[[Catacombs (1965 film)|Catacombs]]'' (1965) - Raymond Garth\n*''[[Ride Beyond Vengeance]]'' (1966) - Dub Stokes\n*''[[Cast a Giant Shadow]]'' (1966) - Pentagon Chief of Staff (scenes deleted)\n*''[[Destination Inner Space]]'' (1966) - Dr. LaSatier\n*''[[Around the World Under the Sea]]'' (1966) - Dr. August 'Gus' Boren\n*''[[The Last Challenge (1967)|The Last Challenge]]'' (1967) - Squint Calloway\n*''[[Clambake (film)|Clambake]]'' (1967) - Sam\n*''[[The Incident (1967 film)|The Incident]]'' (1967) - Douglas McCann\n*''[[The Power (1968 film)|The Power]]'' (1968) - Mark Corlane\n*''[[Pi\u00f9 tardi, Claire, pi\u00f9 tardi]]'' (1968) - George Dennison\n*''[[Amarsi male]]'' (1969)\n*''The Secret of the Sacred Forest'' (1970) - Mike Parks\n*''[[Earth II]]'' (1971) - Walter Dietrich\n*''[[Huckleberry Finn (1974 film)|Huckleberry Finn]]'' (1974) - Pap\n*''[[Thieves]]'' (1977) - Street Man\n*''[[The Seekers (1979 film)|The Seekers]]'' (1979) - Capt. Hull\n*''September Song'' (1984)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Radio appearances==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Program !! Episode/source\n|-\n| 1952|| ''[[Lux Radio Theatre]]'' || ''[[Follow the Sun (film)|Follow the Sun]]''<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kirby|first1=Walter|title=Better Radio Programs for the Week|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/2477300/the_decatur_daily_review/|agency=The Decatur Daily Review|date=March 9, 1952|page=42|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = May 25, 2015}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1952|| ''Hollywood Star Playhouse'' || \"The Patient Stranger\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kirby|first1=Walter|title=Better Radio Programs for the Week|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/2426009/the_decatur_daily_review/|agency=The Decatur Daily Review|date=April 6, 1952|page=52|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = May 16, 2015}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1953|| ''[[Lux Radio Theatre]]'' || ''[[Phone Call from a Stranger]]''<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kirby|first1=Walter|title=Better Radio Programs for the Week|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/2648002/the_decatur_daily_review/|agency=The Decatur Daily Review|date=January 4, 1953|page=38|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = June 19, 2015}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n*{{IMDb name|0581282}}\n*{{IBDB name}}\n*{{Find a Grave|4144}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Merrill, Gary}}\n[[Category:1915 births]]\n[[Category:1990 deaths]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Maine]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male radio actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:Bowdoin College alumni]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in Maine]]\n[[Category:Deaths from lung cancer]]\n[[Category:Maine Democrats]]\n[[Category:People from Falmouth, Maine]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Hartford, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:20th Century Fox contract players]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n", "name_user": "Kaltenmeyer", "label": "safe", "comment": "replaced reference,typo(s) fixed: 1953-1980 \u2192 1953\u20131980", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gary_Merrill"}
{"title_page": "Thomas Coutts (colonist)", "text_new": "'''Thomas Coutts''' (11 December 1797 \u2013 14 January 1868) was a Scottish colonist who moved to Australia during the 19th century establishing various enterprises including [[whaling in Australia|whaling]] and [[pastoral farming]] businesses. He is best known for perpetrating a [[mass poisonings of Aboriginal Australians|mass poisoning]] of [[Aboriginal Australians]] on a property near the [[Clarence River (New South Wales)|Clarence River]] in the [[Northern Rivers]] area of [[New South Wales]], which killed at least 23 people. Although Coutts was arrested for this crime, the judicial authorities never put the case to trial and he was released after the payment of bail. Coutts afterwards became a prosperous and respected colonial figure. The town of [[Coutts Crossing, New South Wales|Coutts Crossing]] is named after him.\n\n==Early life==\nThomas Coutts was born in [[Glenmuick]], [[Aberdeenshire]] in [[Scotland]] on 11 December 1797. His parents were James and Elizabeth Coutts.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Gordon Family Tree |url=https://sites.rootsweb.com/~gordon/gordonfam/pafg43.htm#1345 |website=Rootsweb |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> He emigrated with two of his brothers to the British colony of New South Wales around 1817. He settled in Sydney and it appears that Coutts chose to follow a seafaring vocation. By the 1830s he became a [[master mariner]], taking the title of Captain Thomas Coutts.<ref name=\"couttsclan\">{{cite web |last1=Coutts |first1=Malcolm |title=Capt Thomas & Rev James |url=https://clancoutts.ning.com/page/capt-thomas-rev-james |website=Clan Coutts Society |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Whaling==\nIn 1832, Coutts and his brothers built a 90 tonne [[brig]] on the banks of the [[Georges River]]. They named the vessel the ''Lady Leith'' and Thomas Coutts was registered as both the owner and master of the brig. Initially the ''Lady Leith'' was utilised to transport cargo from Sydney to [[Hobart]] but soon was trading in sugar between [[Mauritius]] and Australia. It seems this wasn't a profitable trade as Coutts quickly switched to using his vessel as a whaler.<ref name=\"couttsclan\" /> From the mid 1830s until 1840, Coutts captained the ''Lady Leith'' in regular voyages to the whaling grounds off New Zealand, returning with cargoes of [[sperm whale]] oil for sale in Sydney.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article31722620 |title=Projected Departures|newspaper=[[The Colonist]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=23 February 1839 |access-date=5 April 2020 |page=2 |via=Trove }}</ref> During this period, Coutts married Maria Bloodworth in 1834 and bought a house in O'Connell Street in Sydney.<ref name=\"couttsfam\">{{cite web |title=Thomas Coutts |url=http://www.whosyerdad-e.com/families-w/individual.php?pid=I2292&ged=white.ged |website=whosyerdad-e |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Pastoral farming==\nIn early 1840, Coutts placed the ''Lady Leith'' up for sale and started to invest in [[pastoral farming]]. He and several other [[Squatting (Australian history)|squatters]] took the opportunity of purchasing and droving herds of livestock to the [[Clarence River (New South Wales)|Clarence River]] region where they could occupy supposedly vacant crown land. They were guided by an ex-convict in [[Richard Craig (adventurer)|Richard Craig]] who had previously lived with the [[Gumbaynggirr]] and [[Bundjalung people]] in this area after he escaped from the [[Moreton Bay penal settlement]]. Initially Coutts set up a [[sheep station]] called Bald Hills in the [[New England (New South Wales)|New England]] region which was at the start of the track down to the Clarence River valley. Coutts Water which was part of his Bald Hills property, is a waterway that still bears his name and is now a popular trout fishing site.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coutts Water |url=https://mapio.net/pic/p-37539788/ |website=mapio |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1840, Coutts, led by Richard Craig, brought around two thousand head of sheep and cattle down the track from Bald Hills to the Clarence River valley.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article141476493 |title=Thomas Courts|newspaper=[[Dungog Chronicle : Durham and Gloucester Advertiser]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=27 April 1934 |access-date=5 April 2020 |page=6 |via=Trove }}</ref> He laid claim to a region of open and lightly wooded country south of the river and named this leasehold Kangaroo Creek. The region was of course already occupied by [[Aboriginal Australians]] and Coutts proceeded to take ownership of the land forcibly from the original inhabitants. In response, the local Gumbaynggirr people killed Coutts' cattle and sheep and also killed several of Coutts' stockmen.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article193844192 |title=Clarence River Historical Society |newspaper=[[Daily Examiner]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=3 July 1937 |access-date=5 April 2020 |page=6 |via=Trove }}</ref> Detachments of [[Border Police of New South Wales|Border Police]] occasionally massacred local Aboriginal people in punitive expeditions in order to protect the local British squatters, but small scale Aboriginal resistance around Kangaroo Creek continued throughout the 1840s.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article28651627 |title=Domestic Intelligence|newspaper=[[The Sydney Herald]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=9 July 1841 |access-date=5 April 2020 |page=2 |via=Trove }}</ref>\n\n==Mass poisoning at Kangaroo Creek==\nIn late November 1847, Coutts invited the Aboriginal people living around Kangaroo Creek to come to his homestead for the possibility of obtaining work. Coutts had previously not allowed any groups of Aboriginal people near his homestead and was widely known to have expressed the opinion that native people \"deserved shooting\".{{cite quote|date=April 2020}} Around 23 people accepted the offer and Coutts put them to work weeding areas close to the homestead. After the work was completed, Coutts gave them a 10-pound bag of flour. Coutts was observed to have put the powdery contents of a paper sachet, believed to have been [[arsenic]], into the bag of flour before giving it to the group of Gumbaynggirr. The unsuspecting people took the bag of poisoned flour from Coutts and proceeded to a communal area in the hills between Kangaroo and Towallum Creeks. Here, they made damper from the flour and ate it.<ref name=\"lydon\" >{{Citation | author1=Lydon, Jane | title='no moral doubt...' : Aboriginal evidence and the Kangaroo Creek poisoning, 1847\u20131849 | publication-date=1996 | url=https://press-files.anu.edu.au/downloads/press/p72561/pdf/article0714.pdf | accessdate=5 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article141476489 |title=Poisoned Blacks|newspaper=[[Dungog Chronicle : Durham and Gloucester Advertiser]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=27 April 1934 |access-date=5 April 2020 |page=6 |via=Trove }}</ref>\n\nA couple of days later, several reports emerged of a large number of Aboriginal people becoming violently ill and dying in the hills behind Kangaroo Creek. The local Commissioner for Crown Lands, Oliver Fry, heard these reports from both white and black sources, and came to investigate. In January 1848, Fry visited the site and found the decomposing bodies of at least 23 people. He collected evidence including remnants of the damper that remained, and immediately arrested and charged Coutts for the crime. Local magistrates concluded Coutts should stand trial for wilful murder and he was transported to Sydney to be tried at the Supreme Court.<ref name=\"lydon\" />\n\nOn 23 February, Coutts appeared before judge [[Alfred Stephen]] and was given bail on \u00a31,000 worth of sureties. The case was delayed and on 10 May 1848, the Attorney General, [[John Plunkett]], decided not to proceed with the case. Plunkett did this even though he had a very strong suspicion of Coutts' guilt and was aware that justice was being \"entirely evaded\" by this decision. Coutts was subsequently discharged and returned to Kangaroo Creek.<ref name=\"lydon\" />\n\n==Moving northwards==\nDuring his time at Sydney, one of Coutts' hutkeepers at Kangaroo Creek was killed by local Gumbaynggirr in an apparent revenge attack. Coutts quickly sold out of his Kangaroo Creek holdings and in 1850 he took up the [[Tooloom Creek|Tooloom]] property in the ranges about 100&nbsp;km to the north of [[Grafton, New South Wales|Grafton]]. He also invested in a steamer named the ''Raven'' which provided a river transport service between [[Brisbane]] and [[Ipswich, Queensland|Ipswich]]. In 1851, Coutts looked to gain further property by taking a large flock of sheep further north to squat on land near to [[Camboon, Queensland|Camboon]] on the [[Dawson River (Queensland)|Dawson River]]. This region was being strongly defended from British colonisation by the resident [[Yiman people]] who killed several of Coutts' shepherds and speared to death Alexander \"Sandy\" Ross, who was a squatter accompanying Coutts in his attempt to set up a property. Due to the resistance of the Yiman, Coutts was forced to abandon the Dawson River and returned to Tooloom.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article677024 |title=Central Criminal Court|newspaper=[[The Maitland Mercury and Hunter River General Advertiser]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=6 December 1851 |access-date=5 April 2020 |page=2 |via=Trove }}</ref> A few years later, he bought the [[Ellangowan, Queensland|Ellangowan]] property near [[Toowoomba]]. His wife died at this property in 1856 and the following year Coutts sold the ''Raven''.\n\n==Later life==\nIn 1859, Coutts decided to retire from the violent yet profitable frontier pastoralist lifestyle and bought a mansion in the waterside Sydney suburb of [[Balmain, New South Wales|Balmain]] where he stayed until 1866.<ref name=\"couttsclan\" /> The residence he purchased, known as \"Balmoral House\", still exists today under that name at 46 Waterview Street in Balmain.<ref>{{cite web |title=Balmoral House |url=https://balmainwalks.org.au/tb_walk_stop/balmoral-house/ |website=Balmain Walks |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> In 1866, Coutts decided to return to the land and purchased the [[Toolburra, Queensland|North Toolburra]] property near [[Warwick, Queensland|Warwick]] in the recently created British colony of [[Queensland]]. By this stage, this area was hundreds of kilometres within the brutal frontier of British invasion but Coutts still managed to meet his death at Toolburra soon after moving there. In January 1868, Coutts walked under a tree that was being felled on this property and was hit on the head by a large branch which killed him instantly. A large funeral was organised at Warwick and he is buried in the Coutts family plot at [[Warwick General Cemetery]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article82096059 |title=The Accidental Death of Thomas Coutts, Esq. |newspaper=[[Warwick Examiner and Times]] |location=Queensland, Australia |date=18 January 1868 |access-date=5 April 2020 |page=2 |via=Trove }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Thomas Coutts |url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/181981281/thomas-coutts |website=Find a Grave |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Family and legacy==\nThomas Coutts had two notable brothers, one of which was Donald Coutts who accompanied Thomas throughout most of his pastoral pursuits. Donald took over the running of Tooloom from Thomas and also took up the Rosewood leasehold near Ipswich. Donald, like Thomas, was involved in a number of major incidents of frontier violence with Aboriginal people.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article3716180 |title=Local Intelligence|newspaper=[[The Moreton Bay Courier]] |location=Queensland, Australia |date=5 September 1846 |access-date=5 April 2020 |page=2 |via=Trove }}</ref> Thomas' other brother was Reverend James Coutts who was a minister at [[Parramatta]] and then [[Newcastle, New South Wales|Newcastle]] and is known for the establishment of the [[Coutt's Sailors Home]] in the latter city.<ref name=\"couttsclan\" />\n\nThomas Coutts had nine children with Maria Bloodworth with many marrying into well respected colonial families.<ref name=\"couttsfam\" />\n\nSeveral landmarks are named after Thomas Coutts. This includes town of [[Coutts Crossing, New South Wales|Coutts Crossing]] near [[Grafton, New South Wales|Grafton]], the distinctive mountain outside the town of [[Urbenville, New South Wales|Urbenville]] known as Coutts Crown, and the Coutts Water stream near [[Ebor, New South Wales|Ebor]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article191783247 |title=Clarence River Historical Society |newspaper=[[The Daily Examiner]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=15 October 1938 |access-date=5 April 2020 |page=8 |via=Trove }}</ref> In 2018, a vote was taken by the residents of Coutts Crossing to rename their town to avoid being associated with Thomas Coutts. The residents overwhelmingly decided to retain Coutts Crossing as the town's title.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Harper |first1=Donna |title=Coutts Crossing villagers vote against name change despite links to brutal past |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-06-29/coutts-crossing-residents-keep-town-name-despite-a-murky-past/9921206 |accessdate=5 April 2020 |agency=ABC News |date=5 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Coutts, Thomas}}\n[[Category:1797 deaths]]\n[[Category:1868 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Aberdeenshire]]\n[[Category:Australian pastoralists]]\n[[Category:Poisoners]]\n", "text_old": "'''Thomas Coutts''' (11 December 1797 \u2013 14 January 1868) was a Scottish colonist who moved to Australia during the 19th century establishing various enterprises including [[whaling in Australia|whaling]] and [[pastoral farming]] businesses. He is best known for perpetrating a [[mass poisonings of Aboriginal Australians|mass poisoning]] of [[Aboriginal Australians]] on a property near the [[Clarence River (New South Wales)|Clarence River]] in the [[Northern Rivers]] area of [[New South Wales]], which killed at least 23 people. Although Coutts was arrested for this crime, the judicial authorities never put the case to trial and he was released after the payment of bail. Coutts afterwards became a prosperous and respected colonial figure. The town of [[Coutts Crossing, New South Wales|Coutts Crossing]] is named after him.\n\n==Early life==\nThomas Coutts was born in [[Glenmuick]], [[Aberdeenshire]] in [[Scotland]] on 11 December 1797. His parents were James and Elizabeth Coutts.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Gordon Family Tree |url=https://sites.rootsweb.com/~gordon/gordonfam/pafg43.htm#1345 |website=Rootsweb |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> He emigrated with two of his brothers to the British colony of New South Wales around 1817. He settled in Sydney and it appears that Coutts chose to follow a seafaring vocation. By the 1830s he became a [[master mariner]], taking the title of Captain Thomas Coutts.<ref name=\"couttsclan\">{{cite web |last1=Coutts |first1=Malcolm |title=Capt Thomas & Rev James |url=https://clancoutts.ning.com/page/capt-thomas-rev-james |website=Clan Coutts Society |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Whaling==\nIn 1832, Coutts and his brothers built a 90 tonne [[brig]] on the banks of the [[Georges River]]. They named the vessel the ''Lady Leith'' and Thomas Coutts was registered as both the owner and master of the brig. Initially the ''Lady Leith'' was utilised to transport cargo from Sydney to [[Hobart]] but soon was trading in sugar between [[Mauritius]] and Australia. It seems this wasn't a profitable trade as Coutts quickly switched to using his vessel as a whaler.<ref name=\"couttsclan\" /> From the mid 1830s until 1840, Coutts captained the ''Lady Leith'' in regular voyages to the whaling grounds off New Zealand, returning with cargoes of [[sperm whale]] oil for sale in Sydney.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article31722620 |title=Projected Departures|newspaper=[[The Colonist]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=23 February 1839 |access-date=5 April 2020 |page=2 |via=Trove }}</ref> During this period, Coutts married Maria Bloodworth in 1834 and bought a house in O'Connell Street in Sydney.<ref name=\"couttsfam\">{{cite web |title=Thomas Coutts |url=http://www.whosyerdad-e.com/families-w/individual.php?pid=I2292&ged=white.ged |website=whosyerdad-e |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Pastoral farming==\nIn early 1840, Coutts placed the ''Lady Leith'' up for sale and started to invest in [[pastoral farming]]. He and several other [[Squatting (Australian history)|squatters]] took the opportunity of purchasing and droving herds of livestock to the [[Clarence River (New South Wales)|Clarence River]] region where they could occupy supposedly vacant crown land. They were guided by an ex-convict in [[Richard Craig (adventurer)|Richard Craig]] who had previously lived with the [[Gumbaynggirr]] and [[Bundjalung people]] in this area after he escaped from the [[Moreton Bay penal settlement]]. Initially Coutts set up a [[sheep station]] called Bald Hills in the [[New England (New South Wales)|New England]] region which was at the start of the track down to the Clarence River valley. Coutts Water which was part of his Bald Hills property, is a waterway that still bears his name and is now a popular trout fishing site.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coutts Water |url=https://mapio.net/pic/p-37539788/ |website=mapio |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1840, Coutts, led by Richard Craig, brought around two thousand head of sheep and cattle down the track from Bald Hills to the Clarence River valley.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article141476493 |title=Thomas Courts|newspaper=[[Dungog Chronicle : Durham and Gloucester Advertiser]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=27 April 1934 |access-date=5 April 2020 |page=6 |via=Trove }}</ref> He laid claim to a region of open and lightly wooded country south of the river and named this leasehold Kangaroo Creek. The region was of course already occupied by [[Aboriginal Australians]] and Coutts proceeded to take ownership of the land forcibly from the original inhabitants. In response, the local Gumbaynggirr people killed Coutts' cattle and sheep and also killed several of Coutts' stockmen.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article193844192 |title=Clarence River Historical Society |newspaper=[[Daily Examiner]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=3 July 1937 |access-date=5 April 2020 |page=6 |via=Trove }}</ref> Detachments of [[Border Police of New South Wales|Border Police]] occassionally massacred local Aboriginal people in punitive expeditions in order to protect the local British squatters, but small scale Aboriginal resistance around Kangaroo Creek continued throughout the 1840s.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article28651627 |title=Domestic Intelligence|newspaper=[[The Sydney Herald]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=9 July 1841 |access-date=5 April 2020 |page=2 |via=Trove }}</ref>\n\n==Mass poisoning at Kangaroo Creek==\nIn late November 1847, Coutts invited the Aboriginal people living around Kangaroo Creek to come to his homestead for the possibility of obtaining work. Coutts had previously not allowed any groups of Aboriginal people near his homestead and was widely known to have expressed the opinion that native people \"deserved shooting\".{{cite quote|date=April 2020}} Around 23 people accepted the offer and Coutts put them to work weeding areas close to the homestead. After the work was completed, Coutts gave them a 10 pound bag of flour. Coutts was observed to have put the powdery contents of a paper sachet, believed to have been [[arsenic]], into the bag of flour before giving it to the group of Gumbaynggirr. The unsuspecting people took the bag of poisoned flour from Coutts and proceeded to a communal area in the hills between Kangaroo and Towallum Creeks. Here, they made damper from the flour and ate it.<ref name=\"lydon\" >{{Citation | author1=Lydon, Jane | title='no moral doubt...' : Aboriginal evidence and the Kangaroo Creek poisoning, 1847\u20131849 | publication-date=1996 | url=https://press-files.anu.edu.au/downloads/press/p72561/pdf/article0714.pdf | accessdate=5 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article141476489 |title=Poisoned Blacks|newspaper=[[Dungog Chronicle : Durham and Gloucester Advertiser]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=27 April 1934 |access-date=5 April 2020 |page=6 |via=Trove }}</ref>\n\nA couple of days later, several reports emerged of a large number of Aboriginal people becoming violently ill and dying in the hills behind Kangaroo Creek. The local Commissioner for Crown Lands, Oliver Fry, heard these reports from both white and black sources, and came to investigate. In January 1848, Fry visited the site and found the decomposing bodies of at least 23 people. He collected evidence including remnants of the damper that remained, and immediately arrested and charged Coutts for the crime. Local magistrates concluded Coutts should stand trial for wilful murder and he was transported to Sydney to be tried at the Supreme Court.<ref name=\"lydon\" />\n\nOn 23 February, Coutts appeared before judge [[Alfred Stephen]] and was given bail on \u00a31,000 worth of sureties. The case was delayed and on 10 May 1848, the Attorney General, [[John Plunkett]], decided not to proceed with the case. Plunkett did this even though he had a very strong suspicion of Coutts' guilt and was aware that justice was being \"entirely evaded\" by this decision. Coutts was subsequently discharged and returned to Kangaroo Creek.<ref name=\"lydon\" />\n\n==Moving northwards==\nDuring his time at Sydney, one of Coutts' hutkeepers at Kangaroo Creek was killed by local Gumbaynggirr in an apparent revenge attack. Coutts quickly sold out of his Kangaroo Creek holdings and in 1850 he took up the [[Tooloom Creek|Tooloom]] property in the ranges about 100km to the north of [[Grafton, New South Wales|Grafton]]. He also invested in a steamer named the ''Raven'' which provided a river transport service between [[Brisbane]] and [[Ipswich, Queensland|Ipswich]]. In 1851, Coutts looked to gain further property by taking a large flock of sheep further north to squat on land near to [[Camboon, Queensland|Camboon]] on the [[Dawson River (Queensland)|Dawson River]]. This region was being strongly defended from British colonisation by the resident [[Yiman people]] who killed several of Coutts' shepherds and speared to death Alexander \"Sandy\" Ross, who was a squatter accompanying Coutts in his attempt to set up a property. Due to the resistance of the Yiman, Coutts was forced to abandon the Dawson River and returned to Tooloom.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article677024 |title=Central Criminal Court|newspaper=[[The Maitland Mercury and Hunter River General Advertiser]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=6 December 1851 |access-date=5 April 2020 |page=2 |via=Trove }}</ref> A few years later, he bought the [[Ellangowan, Queensland|Ellangowan]] property near [[Toowoomba]]. His wife died at this property in 1856 and the following year Coutts sold the ''Raven''.\n\n==Later life==\nIn 1859, Coutts decided to retire from the violent yet profitable frontier pastoralist lifestyle and bought a mansion in the waterside Sydney suburb of [[Balmain, New South Wales|Balmain]] where he stayed until 1866.<ref name=\"couttsclan\" /> The residence he purchased, known as \"Balmoral House\", still exists today under that name at 46 Waterview Street in Balmain.<ref>{{cite web |title=Balmoral House |url=https://balmainwalks.org.au/tb_walk_stop/balmoral-house/ |website=Balmain Walks |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> In 1866, Coutts decided to return to the land and purchased the [[Toolburra, Queensland|North Toolburra]] property near [[Warwick, Queensland|Warwick]] in the recently created British colony of [[Queensland]]. By this stage, this area was hundreds of kilometres within the brutal frontier of British invasion but Coutts still managed to meet his death at Toolburra soon after moving there. In January 1868, Coutts walked under a tree that was being felled on this property and was hit on the head by a large branch which killed him instantly. A large funeral was organised at Warwick and he is buried in the Coutts family plot at [[Warwick General Cemetery]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article82096059 |title=The Accidental Death of Thomas Coutts, Esq. |newspaper=[[Warwick Examiner and Times]] |location=Queensland, Australia |date=18 January 1868 |access-date=5 April 2020 |page=2 |via=Trove }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Thomas Coutts |url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/181981281/thomas-coutts |website=Find a Grave |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Family and legacy==\nThomas Coutts had two notable brothers, one of which was Donald Coutts who accompanied Thomas throughout most of his pastoral pursuits. Donald took over the running of Tooloom from Thomas and also took up the Rosewood leasehold near Ipswich. Donald, like Thomas, was involved in a number of major incidents of frontier violence with Aboriginal people.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article3716180 |title=Local Intelligence|newspaper=[[The Moreton Bay Courier]] |location=Queensland, Australia |date=5 September 1846 |access-date=5 April 2020 |page=2 |via=Trove }}</ref> Thomas' other brother was Reverend James Coutts who was a minister at [[Parramatta]] and then [[Newcastle, New South Wales|Newcastle]] and is known for the establishment of the [[Coutt's Sailors Home]] in the latter city.<ref name=\"couttsclan\" />\n\nThomas Coutts had nine children with Maria Bloodworth with many marrying into well respected colonial families.<ref name=\"couttsfam\" />\n\nSeveral landmarks are named after Thomas Coutts. This includes town of [[Coutts Crossing, New South Wales|Coutts Crossing]] near [[Grafton, New South Wales|Grafton]], the distinctive mountain outside the town of [[Urbenville, New South Wales|Urbenville]] known as Coutts Crown, and the Coutts Water stream near [[Ebor, New South Wales|Ebor]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article191783247 |title=Clarence River Historical Society |newspaper=[[The Daily Examiner]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=15 October 1938 |access-date=5 April 2020 |page=8 |via=Trove }}</ref> In 2018, a vote was taken by the residents of Coutts Crossing to rename their town to avoid being associated with Thomas Coutts. The residents overwhelmingly decided to retain Coutts Crossing as the town's title.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Harper |first1=Donna |title=Coutts Crossing villagers vote against name change despite links to brutal past |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-06-29/coutts-crossing-residents-keep-town-name-despite-a-murky-past/9921206 |accessdate=5 April 2020 |agency=ABC News |date=5 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Coutts, Thomas}}\n[[Category:1797 deaths]]\n[[Category:1868 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Aberdeenshire]]\n[[Category:Australian pastoralists]]\n[[Category:Poisoners]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: 10 pound \u2192 10-pound, occassionally \u2192 occasionally", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Coutts_(colonist)"}
{"title_page": "2010 Colombia\u2013Venezuela diplomatic crisis", "text_new": "{| class=\"infobox bordered\"\n|+ '''2010 Colombia\u2013Venezuela diplomatic crisis'''\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"width:300px; text-align:center;\"| {{Flagicon|Colombia|size=100x50px}} {{Flagicon|Venezuela|size=100x50px}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Image:Colombia Venezuela Locator.png|300px]]\n|-\n| {{legend|#e3801c|'''[[Colombia]]'''}}\n| {{legend|#007e00|'''[[Venezuela]]'''}}\n|}\nThe '''2010 Colombia\u2013Venezuela diplomatic crisis''' was a diplomatic stand-off between [[Colombia]] and [[Venezuela]] over allegations in July by Colombian President [[\u00c1lvaro Uribe]] that the Venezuelan government was actively permitting the [[FARC]] and [[National Liberation Army (Colombia)|ELN]] guerrillas to seek safe haven in its territory. Uribe presented evidence to the [[Organization of American States]] (OAS) allegedly drawn from laptops acquired in a raid on a FARC camp in [[Ecuador]] (which had sparked the [[2008 Andean diplomatic crisis]]).\n\nIn response to the allegations Venezuela broke off diplomatic relations, amid speculation of a possible war. The crisis was resolved after [[Juan Manuel Santos]] was inaugurated as the new President of Colombia on {{Nowrap|7 August}} 2010, after the intervention of [[UNASUR]] who brought together Santos and Venezuelan President [[Hugo Ch\u00e1vez]]. Ch\u00e1vez then told the guerrillas that there could be no military solution to the [[Colombian armed conflict (1964\u2013present)|internal Colombia conflict]],<ref>''[[Agence France-Presse|AFP]]'', {{Nowrap|8 August}} 2010, [http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3553251,00.html  Chavez urges Colombian rebels to release all hostages]</ref> and Santos agreed to turn over the disputed laptops to the Ecuadorean government.<ref>''[[Agence France-Presse|AFP]]'', {{Nowrap|10 August}} 2010, [https://www.rnw.org/archive/colombia-venezuela-leaders-expected-renew-ties Colombia, Venezuela, leaders expected to renew ties], archived by [[WebCite]] at https://www.webcitation.org/5rxM1Dosz?url=http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5jNUNLhuoO90FEB6EcE329fVZRrAA</ref> Both countries then agreed to re-establish diplomatic relations.\n\n==Increase in tensions==\nIn reaction to Colombian allegations that there was evidence showing FARC and [[National Liberation Army (Colombia)|ELN]] guerrilla camps established on the Venezuelan side of the border,<ref name=\"CNN Wire Staff\">{{Cite news|title=Venezuela breaks relations with Colombia|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2010/WORLD/americas/07/22/venezuela.colombia/index.html#fbid=d7pnWh_hE1C|accessdate=22 July 2010|newspaper=[[CNN|CNN.com]]|date=22 July 2010}}</ref> Venezuelan Foreign Minister [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]] recalled his country's ambassador to Colombia for \"discussions.\"{{Citation needed|date=July 2010}} Colombia then took their complaint to the [[Organization of American States|OAS]] which planned to hold a special meeting on {{Nowrap|22 July}} to hear the complaint that Venezuela tolerates Colombian rebel camps on its territory.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-10674859 |title=BBC News \u2013 Colombia takes Venezuela rebel accusation to OAS |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=18 July 2010 |accessdate=12 August 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100831145111/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-10674859| archivedate= 31 August 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> On {{Nowrap|22 July}} the Colombian foreign ministry said its ambassador, [[Mar\u00eda Luisa Chiappe]], would be recalled \"to evaluate the situation\", following which they would present evidence at the OAS' emergency meeting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/americas/2010/07/2010722153742742163.html |title=Venezuela cuts ties with Colombia \u2013 Americas |publisher=Al Jazeera English |date=22 July 2010 |accessdate=12 August 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100725154920/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/americas/2010/07/2010722153742742163.html| archivedate= 25 July 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 July, as a press briefing at the [[United States Department of State|US State Department]], a spokesman said \"some of this is not new in the sense that there have been concerns for some time of cross-border interaction involvement in insurgent activities or terrorist activities within Colombia. Venezuela is obliged, as a member of the [[United Nations]], the OAS, and [[UNASUR]], to deny terrorist groups the ability to operate within its territory. We've been concerned about this for some time and it's one of the reasons why, since 2006, Venezuela has been judged not to be fully cooperating on anti-terrorism efforts.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/prs/dpb/2010/07/144770.htm |title=Daily Press Briefing \u2013 July 16 |publisher=State.gov |date=16 July 2010 |accessdate=12 August 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n{{Wikinews|Venezuelan president Hugo Ch\u00e1vez cuts relations with Colombia}}\n\nOn 22 July, Venezuelan President Hugo Ch\u00e1vez announced that \"for dignity's sake\" he was breaking off relations with Colombia as a response to Colombia's accusations.<ref name=\"CNN Wire Staff\"/> [[Bolivia]]n President [[Evo Morales]] called for an emergency meeting of UNASUR to calm tensions in the region. \"I want to ask the head of UNASUR, Ecuadorean President [[Rafael Correa|Correa]], to call an emergency meeting of the 12 presidents of UNASUR so we can resolve these problems between Colombia and Venezuela. A war is in the making and Bolivia, along with the presidents of the UNASUR, should not allow that war to happen between brother countries.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.ir/detail.aspx?id=136126&sectionid=351020706 |title=Bolivia calls for South American summit |publisher=Presstv.ir |date=25 July 2010 |accessdate=12 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nA few days later Ch\u00e1vez threatened to cut off oil exports to the United States if Colombia launched a military attack. \"If there was any armed aggression against Venezuela from Colombian territory or from anywhere else, promoted by the Yankee empire, we would suspend oil shipments to the United States even if we have to eat stones here.\" He also cancelled a trip to Cuba on the grounds that  \"the possibility of an armed aggression against Venezuelan territory from Colombia\" was higher than it has been \"in 100 years.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/americas/2010/07/2010725194648766704.html |title=Venezuela threatens oil cut to US \u2013 Americas |publisher=Al Jazeera English |date=25 July 2010 |accessdate=12 August 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100728085840/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/americas/2010/07/2010725194648766704.html| archivedate= 28 July 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> Venezuela followed this by bolstering its troop presence along the border with Colombia. Franklin M\u00e1rquez, a regional commander for the Venezuelan National Guard, said \"We have a reinforcement of 980 to 1,000 troops for the protection of the border, but there are no unusual operations; we are staying on alert.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.ir/detail.aspx?id=136363&sectionid=351020704 |title=1000 Venezuelan troops sent to border |publisher=Presstv.ir |date=27 July 2010 |accessdate=12 August 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100729045502/http://www.presstv.ir/detail.aspx?id=136363&sectionid=351020704| archivedate= 29 July 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> This was followed by a denial from Colombian President Uribe that plans were underway to attack Venezuela amid Ch\u00e1vez's call that Uribe was \"capable of anything.\" Uribe's spokesman, C\u00e9sar Vel\u00e1squez, said \"Colombia has never thought of attacking [Venezuela], as its president has told his country in a clearly deceptive move. [Colombia] continues to insist [on the application of international law to ensure Venezuela] complies with its obligation not to harbour Colombian terrorists.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/americas/2010/07/201073118199814801.html |title=Uribe denies war plan on Venezuela \u2013 Americas |publisher=Al Jazeera English |date=1 August 2010 |accessdate=12 August 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100805041739/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/americas/2010/07/201073118199814801.html| archivedate= 5 August 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n==Reconciliation==\nOn August 10, just days after Colombia's new president, [[Juan Manuel Santos]], was sworn in at a ceremony attended by Venezuela's Maduro, both he and Chavez agreed to restore bilateral relations and re-establish diplomatic ties \"based on transparent and direct dialogue.\" Santos said he received assurances from Chavez that he would not allow guerrilla groups to set up camp inside Venezuela. The two also expressed optimism that their first meeting would produce positive results.<ref name=NYT>{{cite news|title=Leaders Repair Colombia\u2013Venezuela Ties|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/11/world/americas/11venez.html|accessdate=12 August 2010|newspaper=[[NYT|Nytimes.com]]|date=10 August 2010 | first=Simon | last=Romero}}</ref><ref name=AJ>{{cite news|title=Colombia and Venezuela restore ties|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/americas/2010/08/201081023312716697.html|accessdate=12 August 2010|newspaper=[[Al Jazeera|English.Aljazeera.net]]|date=11 August 2010}}</ref> in [[Santa Marta, Colombia]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Santos/Chavez admits differences but restore diplomatic relations|url=http://en.mercopress.com/2010/08/11/santos-chavez-admits-differences-but-restore-diplomatic-relations|accessdate=12 August 2010|newspaper=[[Mercopress|http://en.mercopress.com/]]|date=12 August 2010}}</ref> This was a result of mediation by [[Union of South American Nations|UNASUR]] [[List of Secretaries General of UNASUR|Secretary General]] [[N\u00e9stor Kirchner]] who said \"We Latin Americans have proved we can solve our own problems.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Kirchner: \"We Latin Americans have proved we can solve our own problems\" |url=http://english.telam.com.ar/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=9909:kirchner-we-latin-americans-have-proved-we-can-solve-our-own-problems&catid=42:politics |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110531171636/http://english.telam.com.ar/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=9909%3Akirchner-we-latin-americans-have-proved-we-can-solve-our-own-problems&catid=42%3Apolitics |url-status=dead |archive-date=31 May 2011 |accessdate=12 August 2010 |newspaper=[[T\u00e9lam|english.telam.com.ar]] |date=11 August 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Hillary Clinton praises Argentina's role in Venezuela-Colombia conflict|url=http://www.buenosairesherald.com/BreakingNews/View/41923|accessdate=12 August 2010|newspaper=[[Buenos Aires Herald|/www.buenosairesherald.com]]|date=12 August 2010}}</ref>    \n    \nThe agreement between the two presidents included the setting up of bilateral commissions related to commercial, economic, social investment, infrastructure and security issues.<ref>{{cite news|title= Colombia, Venezuela Set Up Ministerial Mechanism to Foster Ties|url=http://www.plenglish.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=212342&Itemid=1|accessdate=12 August 2010|newspaper=[[Prensa Latina|/www.plenglish.com]]|date=11 August 2010}}</ref><ref name=PL>{{cite news|title= Colombian FM to Meet with Maduro in Caracas|url=http://www.prensa-latina.cu/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=212426&Itemid=1|accessdate=12 August 2010|newspaper=[[Prensa Latina|/www.plenglish.com]]|date=11 August 2010}}</ref> The agreement stated the objective of enduring stable bilateral relations through adherence to international law, the principles of noninterference in internal affairs, and respect for national sovereignty and territorial integrity.<ref>{{cite news|title=Colombia, Venezuela End Diplomatic Crisis|url=http://www.plenglish.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=212319&Itemid=1|accessdate=12 August 2010|newspaper=[[Prensa Latina|/www.plenglish.com]]|date=11 August 2010}}</ref> Venezuela admitted that Colombia has a legal right to sign military agreements with the United States, \"as long as none of those accords affects the sovereignty of neighbours or becomes a threat.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Chavez admits Colombia can sign military agreements even with the United States|url=http://en.mercopress.com/2010/08/12/chavez-admits-colombia-can-sign-military-agreements-even-with-united-states|accessdate=12 August 2010|newspaper=[[Mercopress|http://en.mercopress.com/]]|date=12 August 2010}}</ref>    \n   \nSantos was upbeat regarding the meeting. \"President Ch\u00e1vez and I are putting the interests of our people above personal conveniences.\". In turn Chavez told Santos, \"Count on my friendship.\" The two presidents pledged to send ambassadors to each other's capital cities, and work on further details involving finance and military issues.<ref name=NYT /> he said he received assurances from Ch\u00e1vez that he would not allow guerrilla groups to set up camp inside Venezuela. Ch\u00e1vez already sent two infantry brigade near borders and air forces to stop any possible FARC activities on Venezuelan territory. The two also expressed optimism that their first meeting would produce positive results.<ref name=AJ /> A large factor in the reconciliation was collapsing trade between the neighbouring countries' economies. ''[[The New York Times]]'' also cited a former U.S. ambassador to Colombia saying that both men were likely to be in power in their nations for much of the coming decade, \"so it would be in both of their interests to learn to get along.\"<ref name=NYT />\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Colombia|Venezuela}}\n* [[Colombia\u2013Venezuela relations]]\n* [[2008 Andean diplomatic crisis]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Colombia conflict}}\n{{Bolivarian Venezuela Crisis|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2010 Colombia-Venezuela Diplomatic Crisis}}\n[[Category:Colombia\u2013Venezuela relations]]\n[[Category:2010 in Colombia|Colombia-Venezuela diplomatic crisis]]\n[[Category:2010 in Venezuela|Colombia-Venezuela diplomatic crisis]]\n", "text_old": "{| class=\"infobox bordered\"\n|+ '''2010 Colombia\u2013Venezuela diplomatic crisis'''\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"width:300px; text-align:center;\"| {{Flagicon|Colombia|size=100x50px}} {{Flagicon|Venezuela|size=100x50px}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Image:Colombia Venezuela Locator.png|300px]]\n|-\n| {{legend|#e3801c|'''[[Colombia]]'''}}\n| {{legend|#0000b0|'''[[Venezuela]]'''}}\n|}\nThe '''2010 Colombia\u2013Venezuela diplomatic crisis''' was a diplomatic stand-off between [[Colombia]] and [[Venezuela]] over allegations in July by Colombian President [[\u00c1lvaro Uribe]] that the Venezuelan government was actively permitting the [[FARC]] and [[National Liberation Army (Colombia)|ELN]] guerrillas to seek safe haven in its territory. Uribe presented evidence to the [[Organization of American States]] (OAS) allegedly drawn from laptops acquired in a raid on a FARC camp in [[Ecuador]] (which had sparked the [[2008 Andean diplomatic crisis]]).\n\nIn response to the allegations Venezuela broke off diplomatic relations, amid speculation of a possible war. The crisis was resolved after [[Juan Manuel Santos]] was inaugurated as the new President of Colombia on {{Nowrap|7 August}} 2010, after the intervention of [[UNASUR]] who brought together Santos and Venezuelan President [[Hugo Ch\u00e1vez]]. Ch\u00e1vez then told the guerrillas that there could be no military solution to the [[Colombian armed conflict (1964\u2013present)|internal Colombia conflict]],<ref>''[[Agence France-Presse|AFP]]'', {{Nowrap|8 August}} 2010, [http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3553251,00.html  Chavez urges Colombian rebels to release all hostages]</ref> and Santos agreed to turn over the disputed laptops to the Ecuadorean government.<ref>''[[Agence France-Presse|AFP]]'', {{Nowrap|10 August}} 2010, [https://www.rnw.org/archive/colombia-venezuela-leaders-expected-renew-ties Colombia, Venezuela, leaders expected to renew ties], archived by [[WebCite]] at https://www.webcitation.org/5rxM1Dosz?url=http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5jNUNLhuoO90FEB6EcE329fVZRrAA</ref> Both countries then agreed to re-establish diplomatic relations.\n\n==Increase in tensions==\nIn reaction to Colombian allegations that there was evidence showing FARC and [[National Liberation Army (Colombia)|ELN]] guerrilla camps established on the Venezuelan side of the border,<ref name=\"CNN Wire Staff\">{{Cite news|title=Venezuela breaks relations with Colombia|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2010/WORLD/americas/07/22/venezuela.colombia/index.html#fbid=d7pnWh_hE1C|accessdate=22 July 2010|newspaper=[[CNN|CNN.com]]|date=22 July 2010}}</ref> Venezuelan Foreign Minister [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]] recalled his country's ambassador to Colombia for \"discussions.\"{{Citation needed|date=July 2010}} Colombia then took their complaint to the [[Organization of American States|OAS]] which planned to hold a special meeting on {{Nowrap|22 July}} to hear the complaint that Venezuela tolerates Colombian rebel camps on its territory.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-10674859 |title=BBC News \u2013 Colombia takes Venezuela rebel accusation to OAS |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=18 July 2010 |accessdate=12 August 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100831145111/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-10674859| archivedate= 31 August 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> On {{Nowrap|22 July}} the Colombian foreign ministry said its ambassador, [[Mar\u00eda Luisa Chiappe]], would be recalled \"to evaluate the situation\", following which they would present evidence at the OAS' emergency meeting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/americas/2010/07/2010722153742742163.html |title=Venezuela cuts ties with Colombia \u2013 Americas |publisher=Al Jazeera English |date=22 July 2010 |accessdate=12 August 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100725154920/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/americas/2010/07/2010722153742742163.html| archivedate= 25 July 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 July, as a press briefing at the [[United States Department of State|US State Department]], a spokesman said \"some of this is not new in the sense that there have been concerns for some time of cross-border interaction involvement in insurgent activities or terrorist activities within Colombia. Venezuela is obliged, as a member of the [[United Nations]], the OAS, and [[UNASUR]], to deny terrorist groups the ability to operate within its territory. We've been concerned about this for some time and it's one of the reasons why, since 2006, Venezuela has been judged not to be fully cooperating on anti-terrorism efforts.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/prs/dpb/2010/07/144770.htm |title=Daily Press Briefing \u2013 July 16 |publisher=State.gov |date=16 July 2010 |accessdate=12 August 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n{{Wikinews|Venezuelan president Hugo Ch\u00e1vez cuts relations with Colombia}}\n\nOn 22 July, Venezuelan President Hugo Ch\u00e1vez announced that \"for dignity's sake\" he was breaking off relations with Colombia as a response to Colombia's accusations.<ref name=\"CNN Wire Staff\"/> [[Bolivia]]n President [[Evo Morales]] called for an emergency meeting of UNASUR to calm tensions in the region. \"I want to ask the head of UNASUR, Ecuadorean President [[Rafael Correa|Correa]], to call an emergency meeting of the 12 presidents of UNASUR so we can resolve these problems between Colombia and Venezuela. A war is in the making and Bolivia, along with the presidents of the UNASUR, should not allow that war to happen between brother countries.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.ir/detail.aspx?id=136126&sectionid=351020706 |title=Bolivia calls for South American summit |publisher=Presstv.ir |date=25 July 2010 |accessdate=12 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nA few days later Ch\u00e1vez threatened to cut off oil exports to the United States if Colombia launched a military attack. \"If there was any armed aggression against Venezuela from Colombian territory or from anywhere else, promoted by the Yankee empire, we would suspend oil shipments to the United States even if we have to eat stones here.\" He also cancelled a trip to Cuba on the grounds that  \"the possibility of an armed aggression against Venezuelan territory from Colombia\" was higher than it has been \"in 100 years.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/americas/2010/07/2010725194648766704.html |title=Venezuela threatens oil cut to US \u2013 Americas |publisher=Al Jazeera English |date=25 July 2010 |accessdate=12 August 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100728085840/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/americas/2010/07/2010725194648766704.html| archivedate= 28 July 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> Venezuela followed this by bolstering its troop presence along the border with Colombia. Franklin M\u00e1rquez, a regional commander for the Venezuelan National Guard, said \"We have a reinforcement of 980 to 1,000 troops for the protection of the border, but there are no unusual operations; we are staying on alert.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.ir/detail.aspx?id=136363&sectionid=351020704 |title=1000 Venezuelan troops sent to border |publisher=Presstv.ir |date=27 July 2010 |accessdate=12 August 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100729045502/http://www.presstv.ir/detail.aspx?id=136363&sectionid=351020704| archivedate= 29 July 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> This was followed by a denial from Colombian President Uribe that plans were underway to attack Venezuela amid Ch\u00e1vez's call that Uribe was \"capable of anything.\" Uribe's spokesman, C\u00e9sar Vel\u00e1squez, said \"Colombia has never thought of attacking [Venezuela], as its president has told his country in a clearly deceptive move. [Colombia] continues to insist [on the application of international law to ensure Venezuela] complies with its obligation not to harbour Colombian terrorists.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/americas/2010/07/201073118199814801.html |title=Uribe denies war plan on Venezuela \u2013 Americas |publisher=Al Jazeera English |date=1 August 2010 |accessdate=12 August 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100805041739/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/americas/2010/07/201073118199814801.html| archivedate= 5 August 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n==Reconciliation==\nOn August 10, just days after Colombia's new president, [[Juan Manuel Santos]], was sworn in at a ceremony attended by Venezuela's Maduro, both he and Chavez agreed to restore bilateral relations and re-establish diplomatic ties \"based on transparent and direct dialogue.\" Santos said he received assurances from Chavez that he would not allow guerrilla groups to set up camp inside Venezuela. The two also expressed optimism that their first meeting would produce positive results.<ref name=NYT>{{cite news|title=Leaders Repair Colombia\u2013Venezuela Ties|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/11/world/americas/11venez.html|accessdate=12 August 2010|newspaper=[[NYT|Nytimes.com]]|date=10 August 2010 | first=Simon | last=Romero}}</ref><ref name=AJ>{{cite news|title=Colombia and Venezuela restore ties|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/americas/2010/08/201081023312716697.html|accessdate=12 August 2010|newspaper=[[Al Jazeera|English.Aljazeera.net]]|date=11 August 2010}}</ref> in [[Santa Marta, Colombia]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Santos/Chavez admits differences but restore diplomatic relations|url=http://en.mercopress.com/2010/08/11/santos-chavez-admits-differences-but-restore-diplomatic-relations|accessdate=12 August 2010|newspaper=[[Mercopress|http://en.mercopress.com/]]|date=12 August 2010}}</ref> This was a result of mediation by [[Union of South American Nations|UNASUR]] [[List of Secretaries General of UNASUR|Secretary General]] [[N\u00e9stor Kirchner]] who said \"We Latin Americans have proved we can solve our own problems.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Kirchner: \"We Latin Americans have proved we can solve our own problems\" |url=http://english.telam.com.ar/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=9909:kirchner-we-latin-americans-have-proved-we-can-solve-our-own-problems&catid=42:politics |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110531171636/http://english.telam.com.ar/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=9909%3Akirchner-we-latin-americans-have-proved-we-can-solve-our-own-problems&catid=42%3Apolitics |url-status=dead |archive-date=31 May 2011 |accessdate=12 August 2010 |newspaper=[[T\u00e9lam|english.telam.com.ar]] |date=11 August 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Hillary Clinton praises Argentina's role in Venezuela-Colombia conflict|url=http://www.buenosairesherald.com/BreakingNews/View/41923|accessdate=12 August 2010|newspaper=[[Buenos Aires Herald|/www.buenosairesherald.com]]|date=12 August 2010}}</ref>    \n    \nThe agreement between the two presidents included the setting up of bilateral commissions related to commercial, economic, social investment, infrastructure and security issues.<ref>{{cite news|title= Colombia, Venezuela Set Up Ministerial Mechanism to Foster Ties|url=http://www.plenglish.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=212342&Itemid=1|accessdate=12 August 2010|newspaper=[[Prensa Latina|/www.plenglish.com]]|date=11 August 2010}}</ref><ref name=PL>{{cite news|title= Colombian FM to Meet with Maduro in Caracas|url=http://www.prensa-latina.cu/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=212426&Itemid=1|accessdate=12 August 2010|newspaper=[[Prensa Latina|/www.plenglish.com]]|date=11 August 2010}}</ref> The agreement stated the objective of enduring stable bilateral relations through adherence to international law, the principles of noninterference in internal affairs, and respect for national sovereignty and territorial integrity.<ref>{{cite news|title=Colombia, Venezuela End Diplomatic Crisis|url=http://www.plenglish.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=212319&Itemid=1|accessdate=12 August 2010|newspaper=[[Prensa Latina|/www.plenglish.com]]|date=11 August 2010}}</ref> Venezuela admitted that Colombia has a legal right to sign military agreements with the United States, \"as long as none of those accords affects the sovereignty of neighbours or becomes a threat.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Chavez admits Colombia can sign military agreements even with the United States|url=http://en.mercopress.com/2010/08/12/chavez-admits-colombia-can-sign-military-agreements-even-with-united-states|accessdate=12 August 2010|newspaper=[[Mercopress|http://en.mercopress.com/]]|date=12 August 2010}}</ref>    \n   \nSantos was upbeat regarding the meeting. \"President Ch\u00e1vez and I are putting the interests of our people above personal conveniences.\". In turn Chavez told Santos, \"Count on my friendship.\" The two presidents pledged to send ambassadors to each other's capital cities, and work on further details involving finance and military issues.<ref name=NYT /> he said he received assurances from Ch\u00e1vez that he would not allow guerrilla groups to set up camp inside Venezuela. Ch\u00e1vez already sent two infantry brigade near borders and air forces to stop any possible FARC activities on Venezuelan territory. The two also expressed optimism that their first meeting would produce positive results.<ref name=AJ /> A large factor in the reconciliation was collapsing trade between the neighbouring countries' economies. ''[[The New York Times]]'' also cited a former U.S. ambassador to Colombia saying that both men were likely to be in power in their nations for much of the coming decade, \"so it would be in both of their interests to learn to get along.\"<ref name=NYT />\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Colombia|Venezuela}}\n* [[Colombia\u2013Venezuela relations]]\n* [[2008 Andean diplomatic crisis]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Colombia conflict}}\n{{Bolivarian Venezuela Crisis|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2010 Colombia-Venezuela Diplomatic Crisis}}\n[[Category:Colombia\u2013Venezuela relations]]\n[[Category:2010 in Colombia|Colombia-Venezuela diplomatic crisis]]\n[[Category:2010 in Venezuela|Colombia-Venezuela diplomatic crisis]]\n", "name_user": "Fahambnd", "label": "safe", "comment": "corrected color-legend (Venezuela)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2010_Colombia%E2%80%93Venezuela_diplomatic_crisis"}
{"title_page": "Sidib\u00e9 Aminata Diallo", "text_new": "'''Sidib\u00e9 Aminata Diallo''' is a [[Mali]]an academic and politician.\n\n==Academia==\nDiallo is a member of the faculty of Economic Sciences and Management at the [[University of Bamako]], where she specializes in land management.<ref name=Cisse>Almahady Ciss\u00e9, [http://allafrica.com/stories/200704250484.html \"A Presidential Election That Breaks With Tradition\"], Inter Press Service (allAfrica.com), 24 April 2007.</ref>\n\n==Politics==\nOn 12 March 2007, Diallo declared her candidacy for the position of [[President of Mali|President]].<ref>[http://apanews.net/article_eng.php3?id_article=23355 \"Malian woman announces candidacy for presidency\"]{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, African Press Agency, 13 March 2007.</ref> She was one of 8 candidates contesting the [[2007 Malian presidential election|April 2007 presidential election]]. She was also the first female presidential candidate ever in Mali and was running as the candidate of the [[Movement for Environmental Education and Sustainable Development]]. Her primary interest is sustainability and environmental protection.<ref name=Cisse/> Diallo received over 12,000 votes in the election, 0.55% of the total.<ref>[http://www.jeuneafrique.com/fluxafp/fil_info.asp?art_cle=36776 \"Pr\u00e9sidentielle au Mali: la Cour constitutionnelle valide la r\u00e9\u00e9lection de Tour\u00e9\"], AFP (Jeuneafrique.com), 12 May 2007 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref>\n\nFollowing the election, Diallo was appointed as Minister of Basic Education, Literacy, and the National Languages on 3 October 2007.<ref>[http://fr.allafrica.com/stories/200710040281.html \"Mali: Amadou Toumani Tour\u00e9 remanie\"], republicoftogo.com (allAfrica.com), 3 October 2007 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref> She held that position until being replaced by [[Salikou Sanogo]] on 9 April 2009.<ref>[http://www.essor.gov.ml/jour/cgi-bin/view_article.pl?id=21886 \"LE NOUVEAU GOUVERNEMENT\"]{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, ''L'Essor'', 10 April 2009 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Diallo, Sidibe Aminata}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Malian environmentalists]]\n[[Category:Movement for Environmental Education and Sustainable Development politicians]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Mali]]\n[[Category:Malian women academics]]\n[[Category:Malian academics]]\n[[Category:University of Bamako faculty]]\n[[Category:21st-century women politicians]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of Mali]]\n\n\n{{Mali-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Sidib\u00e9 Aminata Diallo''' is a [[Mali]]an academic and politician.\n\n==Academia==\nDiallo is a member of the faculty of Economic Sciences and Management at the [[University of Bamako]], where she specializes in land management.<ref name=Cisse>Almahady Ciss\u00e9, [http://allafrica.com/stories/200704250484.html \"A Presidential Election That Breaks With Tradition\"], Inter Press Service (allAfrica.com), 24 April 2007.</ref>\n\n==Politics==\nOn 12 March 2007, Diallo declared her candidacy for the position of [[President of Mali|President]].<ref>[http://apanews.net/article_eng.php3?id_article=23355 \"Malian woman announces candidacy for presidency\"]{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, African Press Agency, 13 March 2007.</ref> She was one of 8 candidates contesting the [[2007 Malian presidential election|April 2007 presidential election]]. She was also the first female presidential candidate ever in Mali and was running as the candidate of the [[Movement for Environmental Education and Sustainable Development]]. Her primary interest is sustainability and environmental protection.<ref name=Cisse/> Diallo received over 12,000 votes in the election, 0.55% of the total.<ref>[http://www.jeuneafrique.com/fluxafp/fil_info.asp?art_cle=36776 \"Pr\u00e9sidentielle au Mali: la Cour constitutionnelle valide la r\u00e9\u00e9lection de Tour\u00e9\"], AFP (Jeuneafrique.com), 12 May 2007 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref>\n\nFollowing the election, Diallo was appointed as Minister of Basic Education, Literacy, and the National Languages on 3 October 2007.<ref>[http://fr.allafrica.com/stories/200710040281.html \"Mali: Amadou Toumani Tour\u00e9 remanie\"], republicoftogo.com (allAfrica.com), 3 October 2007 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref> She held that position until being replaced by [[Salikou Sanogo]] on 9 April 2009.<ref>[http://www.essor.gov.ml/jour/cgi-bin/view_article.pl?id=21886 \"LE NOUVEAU GOUVERNEMENT\"]{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, ''L'Essor'', 10 April 2009 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Diallo, Sidibe Aminata}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Malian environmentalists]]\n[[Category:Movement for Environmental Education and Sustainable Development politicians]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Mali]]\n[[Category:Malian women academics]]\n[[Category:Malian academics]]\n[[Category:University of Bamako faculty]]\n[[Category:21st-century women politicians]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of Mali]]\n\n\n{{Mali-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sidib%C3%A9_Aminata_Diallo"}
{"title_page": "Titus II Teachers College, Thiruvalla", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{ use indian english| date = April 2020}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name = Titus II Teachers College, Thiruvalla\n|Parent = \n|motto    = \"Lighted to Lighten\"\n|established   =1957\n|parent  = Mar Thoma Syrian Church\n|affiliations = [[Mahatma Gandhi University]]\n\n|principal = Dr. Anitha Mathai\n\n|state = Kerala\n\n| website =   [http://tituscollege.ac.in/]     }}\n''' Titus II Teachers College''' was established in 1957 and run by Mar Thoma Syrian Church and is dedicated to the revered memory of His Grace the Most Rev. Titus II, who was Metropolitan of the Mar Thoma Syrian Church from 1898 to 1944. [[National Assessment and Accreditation Council]] (NAAC) reaccredited the college with 'A' grade in 2014. Titus II is affiliated to [[M G University]].\n\n==Courses==\n* B Ed Degree programme\n* M Ed programme\n\n==References==\n[http://tituscollege.ac.in/]\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{ use indian english| date = April 2020}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name = Titus II Teachers College, Thiruvalla\n|Parent = \n|motto    = \"Lighted to Lighten\"\n|established   =1957\n|parent  = Mar Thoma Syrian Church\n|affiliations = [[Mahatma Gandhi University]]\n\n|principal = Dr. Anitha Mathai\n\n|state = Kerala\n\n| website =   [http://tituscollege.ac.in/]     }}\n''' Titus II Teachers College''' was established in 1957 and run by Mar Thoma Syrian Church and is dedicated to the revered memory of His Grace the Most Rev. Titus II, who was Metropolitan of the Mar Thoma Syrian Church from 1898 to 1944. [[National Assessment and Accreditation Council]] (NAAC) reaccredited the college with 'A' grade in 2014. Titus II is affiliated to [[M G University]].\n\n==Courses==\n* B Ed Degree programme\n* M Ed programme\n\n==Reference==\n[http://tituscollege.ac.in/]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u