{"title_page": "Andrew Piddington", "text_new": "'''Andrew J. Piddington''' (born October 18, 1949 in [[Romford]], Essex) is an English film and television director, screenwriter, and producer.\n\n==Career==\nHe directed films such as ''[[Shuttlecock (film)|Shuttlecock]]'' (1991), ''[[The Fall (1999 film)|The Fall]]'' (1999), ''[[The Dinosaur Hunters]]'' (2002) and ''[[The Killing of John Lennon]]'' (2006).<ref name=\"Newton2012\">{{cite book|last=Newton|first=Michael|title=Age of Assassins: A History of Conspiracy and Political Violence, 1865-1981|url=https://archive.org/details/ageofassassinshi0000newt|url-access=registration|date=16 October 2012|publisher=Faber & Faber|isbn=978-0-571-29046-8|page=[https://archive.org/details/ageofassassinshi0000newt/page/725 725]}}</ref> The low-budget ''The Killing of John Lennon'' starred [[Jonas Ball]] as Lennon's killer [[Mark David Chapman]], and was screened at the [[Edinburgh Film Festival|Edinburgh]] and [[Rotterdam Film Festival]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-159178053.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181115052140/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-159178053.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=15 November 2018|title=Lennon pic bought|publisher=Daily Variety, accessed via HighBeam Research {{subscription}}|date=16 January 2007|accessdate=17 September 2014}}</ref> In 1990 he directed the documentary ''[[Hidden Heritage: The Roots of Black American Painting]]'' featuring [[David Driskell]],<ref>{{cite book|title=Arts TV: A History of Arts Television in Britain|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wYjN74Ej-JUC&pg=PA32|year=1993|publisher=Indiana University Press|isbn=0-86196-435-7|page=32}}</ref> funded by the [[Arts Council of Great Britain]] and produced by [[Maureen McCue]].<ref name=\"McGeeDriskell2006\">{{cite book|last1=McGee|first1=Julie L.|last2=Driskell|first2=David C.|title=David C. Driskell: Artist and Scholar|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_wh0ayUOkV0C&pg=PA151|year=2006|publisher=Pomegranate|isbn=978-0-7649-3747-7|page=151}}</ref> In 1996 he directed the series ''[[SAS: The Soldiers' Story]]'', featuring soldiers in different wars and locations in each of the seven episodes, including the [[Falklands War]], the [[Gulf War]], and in Northern Ireland.\n\n==Personal life==\nPiddington was first married to Christine Spencer. He is currently married to Pearl Morrison, who has worked as a script adviser on his films,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/517736/Shuttlecock/|title=Shuttlecock|publisher=TCM|accessdate=17 September 2014}}</ref> and the couple have two children.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0682061}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Piddington, Andrew}}\n[[Category:English film directors]]\n[[Category:English television directors]]\n[[Category:English screenwriters]]\n[[Category:English male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:English film producers]]\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Romford]]\n", "text_old": "'''Andrew J. Piddington''' (born October 18, 1949 in [[Romford]], Essex) is an English film and television director, screenwriter, and producer.\n\n==Career==\nHe directed films such as ''[[Shuttlecock (film)|Shuttlecock]]'' (1991), ''[[The Fall (1999 film)|The Fall]]'' (1999), ''[[The Dinosaur Hunters]]'' (2002) and ''[[The Killing of John Lennon]]'' (2006).<ref name=\"Newton2012\">{{cite book|last=Newton|first=Michael|title=Age of Assassins: A History of Conspiracy and Political Violence, 1865-1981|url=https://archive.org/details/ageofassassinshi0000newt|url-access=registration|date=16 October 2012|publisher=Faber & Faber|isbn=978-0-571-29046-8|page=[https://archive.org/details/ageofassassinshi0000newt/page/725 725]}}</ref> The low-budget ''The Killing of John Lennon'' starred [[Jonas Ball]] as Lennon's killer [[Mark David Chapman]], and was screened at the [[Edinburgh Film Festival|Edinburgh]] and [[Rotterdam Film Festival]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-159178053.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181115052140/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-159178053.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=15 November 2018|title=Lennon pic bought|publisher=Daily Variety, accessed via HighBeam Research {{subscription}}|date=16 January 2007|accessdate=17 September 2014}}</ref> In 1990 he directed the documentary ''[[Hidden Heritage: The Roots of Black American Painting]]'' featuring [[David C. Driskell]],<ref>{{cite book|title=Arts TV: A History of Arts Television in Britain|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wYjN74Ej-JUC&pg=PA32|year=1993|publisher=Indiana University Press|isbn=0-86196-435-7|page=32}}</ref> funded by the [[Arts Council of Great Britain]] and produced by [[Maureen McCue]].<ref name=\"McGeeDriskell2006\">{{cite book|last1=McGee|first1=Julie L.|last2=Driskell|first2=David C.|title=David C. Driskell: Artist and Scholar|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_wh0ayUOkV0C&pg=PA151|year=2006|publisher=Pomegranate|isbn=978-0-7649-3747-7|page=151}}</ref> In 1996 he directed the series ''[[SAS: The Soldiers' Story]]'', featuring soldiers in different wars and locations in each of the seven episodes, including the [[Falklands War]], the [[Gulf War]], and in Northern Ireland.\n\n==Personal life==\nPiddington was first married to Christine Spencer. He is currently married to Pearl Morrison, who has worked as a script adviser on his films,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/517736/Shuttlecock/|title=Shuttlecock|publisher=TCM|accessdate=17 September 2014}}</ref> and the couple have two children.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0682061}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Piddington, Andrew}}\n[[Category:English film directors]]\n[[Category:English television directors]]\n[[Category:English screenwriters]]\n[[Category:English male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:English film producers]]\n[[Category:1949 births]]